    </draw:frame><draw:custom-shape text:anchor-type="char" draw:z-index="15" draw:name="Text Box 22" draw:style-name="gr2" draw:text-style-name="P4" svg:width="0.8004in" svg:height="0.4004in" svg:x="5.8189in" svg:y="0.298in">
     <text:p text:style-name="Frame_20_contents">Fig.3</text:p>
     <draw:enhanced-geometry draw:mirror-horizontal="false" draw:mirror-vertical="false" draw:glue-points="?f0 0 0 ?f1 ?f0 ?f2 ?f3 ?f1" draw:text-areas="0 0 ?f3 ?f2" svg:viewBox="0 0 0 0" draw:type="ooxml-rect" draw:enhanced-path="M 0 0 L ?f3 0 ?f3 ?f2 0 ?f2 Z N">
      <draw:equation draw:name="f0" draw:formula="logwidth/2"/>
      <draw:equation draw:name="f1" draw:formula="logheight/2"/>
      <draw:equation draw:name="f2" draw:formula="logheight"/>
      <draw:equation draw:name="f3" draw:formula="logwidth"/>
     </draw:enhanced-geometry>
    </draw:custom-shape>Ad esempio se anche la seconda macchina è disposta verticalmente (fig.3 <text:span text:style-name="T1"></text:span>=0<text:span text:style-name="T1"></text:span>) allora abbiamo che i fasci <text:span text:style-name="T2">m</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T4"></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T2">=+k</text:span> ed <text:span text:style-name="T2">m</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T4"></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T2">=-k</text:span> hanno intensità proporzionali ai termini 1 e 0, cioè il fascio <text:span text:style-name="T2">m</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T4"></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T2">=+k</text:span> ha tutta l’intensità ed il fascio <text:span text:style-name="T2">m</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T4"></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T2">=-k</text:span> ha intensità zero. Se invece la seconda macchina è disposta a novanta gradi (fig.4 <text:span text:style-name="T1"></text:span>=90<text:span text:style-name="T1"></text:span>) allora i fasci <text:span text:style-name="T2">m</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T3">90</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T2">=+k</text:span> e <text:span text:style-name="T2">m</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T3">90</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T2">=-k</text:span> hanno intensità proporzionali ai termini ½ ed ½, cioè sono uguali.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5"><draw:custom-shape text:anchor-type="char" draw:z-index="14" draw:name="Text Box 23" draw:style-name="gr2" draw:text-style-name="P4" svg:width="0.8004in" svg:height="0.4004in" svg:x="5.8189in" svg:y="0.4362in">
     <text:p text:style-name="Frame_20_contents">Fig.4</text:p>
     <draw:enhanced-geometry draw:mirror-horizontal="false" draw:mirror-vertical="false" draw:glue-points="?f0 0 0 ?f1 ?f0 ?f2 ?f3 ?f1" draw:text-areas="0 0 ?f3 ?f2" svg:viewBox="0 0 0 0" draw:type="ooxml-rect" draw:enhanced-path="M 0 0 L ?f3 0 ?f3 ?f2 0 ?f2 Z N">
      <draw:equation draw:name="f0" draw:formula="logwidth/2"/>
      <draw:equation draw:name="f1" draw:formula="logheight/2"/>
      <draw:equation draw:name="f2" draw:formula="logheight"/>
      <draw:equation draw:name="f3" draw:formula="logwidth"/>
     </draw:enhanced-geometry>
    </draw:custom-shape>E’ interessante osservare che già questi primi risultati non si possono spiegare mediante i concetti della meccanica classica.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">Se ruotiamo anche la prima macchina (fig.5) osserviamo che i risultati non cambiano sostanzialmente e, come era facile immaginare, i due fasci uscenti hanno intensità proporzionali ai termini </text:p>
