    </draw:frame><draw:custom-shape text:anchor-type="char" draw:z-index="11" draw:name="Text Box 28" draw:style-name="gr5" draw:text-style-name="P4" svg:width="1.1004in" svg:height="0.5004in" svg:x="5.3189in" svg:y="1.0909in">
     <text:p text:style-name="Frame_20_contents">Fig.7</text:p>
     <draw:enhanced-geometry draw:mirror-horizontal="false" draw:mirror-vertical="false" draw:glue-points="?f0 0 0 ?f1 ?f0 ?f2 ?f3 ?f1" draw:text-areas="0 0 ?f3 ?f2" svg:viewBox="0 0 0 0" draw:type="ooxml-rect" draw:enhanced-path="M 0 0 L ?f3 0 ?f3 ?f2 0 ?f2 Z N">
      <draw:equation draw:name="f0" draw:formula="logwidth/2"/>
      <draw:equation draw:name="f1" draw:formula="logheight/2"/>
      <draw:equation draw:name="f2" draw:formula="logheight"/>
      <draw:equation draw:name="f3" draw:formula="logwidth"/>
     </draw:enhanced-geometry>
    </draw:custom-shape>La figura 7 mostra che con due macchine di Stern-Gerlach è possibile sovrapporre due fasci che sono stati precedentemente separati da una prima macchina. Gli esperimenti di questo paragrafo si basano sulla sovrapposizione di due fasci.</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_3" text:outline-level="3">Esperimento numero 3.</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard"><draw:custom-shape text:anchor-type="char" draw:z-index="10" draw:name="Text Box 35" draw:style-name="gr6" draw:text-style-name="P4" svg:width="0.9004in" svg:height="0.4004in" svg:x="5.5189in" svg:y="0.7937in">
     <text:p text:style-name="Frame_20_contents">Fig.8</text:p>
     <draw:enhanced-geometry draw:mirror-horizontal="false" draw:mirror-vertical="false" draw:glue-points="?f0 0 0 ?f1 ?f0 ?f2 ?f3 ?f1" draw:text-areas="0 0 ?f3 ?f2" svg:viewBox="0 0 0 0" draw:type="ooxml-rect" draw:enhanced-path="M 0 0 L ?f3 0 ?f3 ?f2 0 ?f2 Z N">
      <draw:equation draw:name="f0" draw:formula="logwidth/2"/>
      <draw:equation draw:name="f1" draw:formula="logheight/2"/>
      <draw:equation draw:name="f2" draw:formula="logheight"/>
      <draw:equation draw:name="f3" draw:formula="logwidth"/>
     </draw:enhanced-geometry>
    </draw:custom-shape>(Vedi fig.8) La prima macchina dispone gli atomi nello stato <text:span text:style-name="T2">m</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T3">0</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T2">=+k</text:span>, la seconda divide il fascio in due parti che hanno <text:span text:style-name="T2">m</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T3">90</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T2">=+k </text:span>ed <text:span text:style-name="T2">m</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T3">90</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T2">=-k</text:span>, le ultime due ricongiungono il fascio.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">Si eseguono tre misure di <text:span text:style-name="T2">m</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T3">0</text:span> (fig.9).</text:p>
